Flight from Moscow
The collapse of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, market economies, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries have decisively broken off their connections with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
The Czech Republic and Georgia belonged until recently to the latter category.
Their economic and political failure was largely based on – actively supported by Russia – secessionist movements that attempted to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia and South Ossetia, Russia converted its military presence there into "peacekeeping troops" to maintain control.
For a long time, people have feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly heat up.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions - because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to break through to market economy and democracy.
This has also been contributed to by the European Union's "neighbourhood policy".
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Georgia has meanwhile turned to the West, already perilously close to a failed state.
The success of various "color revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also brought about change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms, whose aim is to draw closer to the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia gained independence in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with enormous economic problems, making it unsuitable for investment.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and wood, but its economy was growing.
In Northeast Estonia, with its predominantly ethnic Russian population, which had settled here during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called "autonomy movement".
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
Only a few Estonian products were imported into Russia and were subject to high taxes, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerve.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to reorient its economy towards the West.
Western Europe, on the other hand, did what it could to integrate the Baltic States - Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia - and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, an EU free trade agreement enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and so Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries and joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported in the same way by Western Europe.
Although Georgia appeared less attractive as a partner than the Baltic states; the 1990s were characterized by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, in which two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – essentially seceded with the support of Russia.
The country has done its best to forget its hopeless past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army has been strengthened, and the country's leadership is young, dynamic, and zealously working to move the country forward.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% - likely the lowest in the world - the national budget has increased.
The government has increased pensions and enhanced social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is making efforts to ease tensions over Abkhazia and South Ossetia; however, Russia accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
His main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to block reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers at play in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also of importance.
Estonia has shown, in its independence and again in the latest crisis over the relocation of a monument from the Soviet era, that it can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong backing.
Europe needs to realize that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Exactly as the free trade agreement with Europe allowed Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has a legitimate reason to hope that it will achieve real independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were.
The missing reform outcomes are partly the result of the separatist movements supported by Russia.
That the industrialized region of Transnistria, whose population that speaks Russian and Ukrainian was feared, the majority of Moldovans who are of Romanian descent, planned to forge closer ties with Romania, has dealt the country a severe blow to its independence right from the start.
A civil war followed, and in the year 1992, Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they are still today.
The independence of Transnistria has never been recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It's said that lawlessness and corruption reign there.
The Czech Republic is highly indebted, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of its four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Moldovan government representatives have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to make an effort to find a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has asked for help from the EU monitoring team Eubam, but an EU initiative for Russian cooperation would be required.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West is lacking in current knowledge about the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, the EU and the US learned about a proposed peace agreement through a leaked report from Germany.
This, it appears, would favor Russia, as Moldova is supposed to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity within it.
If Russia has thus outmaneuvered the West, this would be a calamitous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
